[
  {
    "eu_id": "EU-0001",
    "kind": "table_panel",
    "page": "jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16",
    "primary_id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_29",
    "source": "visual_seed",
    "member_count": 23,
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_1",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "North Carolina From the beginning, Carolina developed as two separate regions. North Carolina was home to a small and scattered population of farmers. The lack of good harbors hindered growth, and the colony had only 3,000 people by 1700. Eventually, the farmers began growing tobacco for sale. They also used native pine to make and export shipbuilding supplies.",
        "bbox": [
          0.26018150388465106,
          0.06820436486680811,
          0.47397768977021215,
          0.2994186048715877
        ],
        "order": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "asked King George II for a colony south of South Carolina where the poor could start over.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5092936793753887,
          0.0682043649041459,
          0.8921933171301872,
          0.09895833349885207
        ],
        "order": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The English government saw several advantages to a new southern colony. It would help England's poor and provide a strategic buffer to keep Spain from expanding north. King George granted Oglethorpe and his friends permission to settle between the Savannah and Altamaha Rivers. The new colony was named Georgia, in honor of the king, and the first settlers arrived in 1733.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5074349479031688,
          0.10168650802885189,
          0.8940520488099282,
          0.2281976740137817
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_0",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Student Web Activity Visit the American Republic Since 1877 Web site at tarvol2.glencoe.com and click on Student Web Activities— Chapter 2 for an activity on English settlers in America.",
        "bbox": [
          0.07249070670596564,
          0.12053571448190384,
          0.21375464442060857,
          0.2733134922392906
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Oglethorpe and his fellow trustees banned slavery, rum, and brandy in Georgia, and they limited the size of land grants. Still, the colony attracted settlers from all over Europe, including Scotch-Irish, Welsh, Germans, Swiss, and Italians. Increasingly the settlers objected to the colony's strict rules. In the 1740s, the trustees lifted the restrictions on brandy, rum, and slavery, and in 1750, they granted the settlers their own elected assembly. The next year, the trustees gave control back to the king, and Georgia became a royal colony.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5091847719736036,
          0.23110465123957824,
          0.8940520465794451,
          0.40997023794144205
        ],
        "order": 5
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "South Carolina The proprietors of Carolina were always far more interested in the southern half of their holdings, where they hoped to cultivate sugarcane. In 1670 three ships brought settlers from England to South Carolina. They named their first settlement, Charles Town, after the king.",
        "bbox": [
          0.08550186814506988,
          0.31686046563020337,
          0.4739776960680649,
          0.4142441857274761
        ],
        "order": 6
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "By 1775 roughly 2.5 million people lived in England's American colonies. Despite the stumbling start in Jamestown, the English had succeeded in building a large and prosperous society on the east coast of North America.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5092936793753887,
          0.4113372091856462,
          0.8940520383793591,
          0.4883720930527257
        ],
        "order": 7
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The first years of the new colony were difficult. Sugarcane, as it turned out, did not grow well. The first product exported in large quantity was deerskin, popular for English leather. The colony also began to capture and enslave Native Americans, who were shipped to plantations in the Caribbean.",
        "bbox": [
          0.08736060415316871,
          0.41567460297324754,
          0.47211896768780814,
          0.5116567461835408
        ],
        "order": 8
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_16",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "England's success, however, would prove its undoing. By permitting new patterns of land ownership and new types of worship and government in its colonies, the English government had planted the seeds of rebellion.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5074349465296133,
          0.49127906984422937,
          0.8940520409444149,
          0.5683139532285664
        ],
        "order": 9
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_4",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "The Georgia Experiment In the 1720s, General James Oglethorpe, a wealthy member of Parliament, began investigating English prisons. He was appalled to find so many debtors-people who could not pay their debts-behind bars. Oglethorpe",
        "bbox": [
          0.08550186743875016,
          0.5305059522431024,
          0.4721189567867764,
          0.6119186047496735
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_17",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Reading Check Summarizing In what ways was",
        "bbox": [
          0.5334572515636142,
          0.5770348833721141,
          0.869888467639279,
          0.5959821429233713
        ],
        "order": 11
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_18",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "England permissive with its American colonies?",
        "bbox": [
          0.5297397849551373,
          0.5988372091565766,
          0.7973977668664238,
          0.6119186045934236
        ],
        "order": 12
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_jiaocaineedrop_chap02.pdf_16_19",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Study Central™ To review this section, go to tarvol2.glencoe.com and click on Study Central™",
        "bbox": [
          0.5648445946550125,
